{{Infobox treaty | name = Eurasian Patent Convention | long_name = | image = EAPOparties.svg | image_width = 250 px | caption = Parties (purple), former parties (green) and signatories that did not ratify (blue) | type = | date_drafted = | date_signed = {{Start date|1994|09|09|df=y}}<ref name=convention/> | location_signed = [[Moscow]], Russia | date_sealed = | date_effective = 12 August 1995<ref name=history/> | condition_effective = ratification by three States<ref name=convention/> | date_expiration = | negotiators = | signatories = 10 | parties = 8 ([[Armenia]], [[Azerbaijan]], [[Belarus]], [[Russia]], [[Kyrgyzstan]], [[Kazakhstan]], [[Tajikistan]], [[Turkmenistan]])<ref name=history/><ref name=pin/> | depositor = Director-General of [[WIPO]]<ref name=convention/> | language =[[Russian language|Russian]]<ref name=convention/><ref name=pin/> | wikisource = }} The '''Eurasian Patent Convention''' ('''EAPC''') ({{lang-ru|Евразийская патентная конвенция}}) is an international [[patent|patent law]] [[treaty]] instituting both the [[Eurasian Patent Organization]] (EAPO) and the legal system pursuant to which Eurasian patents are granted.<ref name=convention>{{cite web|url=http://www.eapo.org/en/documents/norm/convention_txt.html|title=Eurasian Patent Convention|work=[[Eurasian Patent Organization]]|accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref> It was signed on 9 September 1994 in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]], and entered into force on 12 August 1995.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.eapo.org/eng/ea/patsys/history.html|title=History of the Eurasian patent organization|work=[[Eurasian Patent Organization]]|accessdate=2 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=pin>{{cite journal|date=June 2016|title=Accessing patent information published in Russia – Part 1: Eurasian Patent Office|journal=Patent Information News|publisher=European Patent Office|volume=2016|issue=2|pages=12-14|url=http://documents.epo.org/projects/babylon/eponet.nsf/0/BB3248FC776D2A93C1257FD300318EC8/$File/patent_information_news_0216_en.pdf|accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref>
==History== After the [[Collapse of the Soviet Union]], its successor states had no system for protection of intellectual property. A common patent system was perceived in a convention which was signed on 27 December 1991, but never entered into force.<ref name=history/> This system would provide for a true unitary patent that "may be granted, assigned or canceled in the territory of all the Contracting States with due regard to the invention [[patentability]] criteria provided for in the USSR legislation". The second version of the convention went less far: in line with the [[European Patent Convention]],<ref name=pin/> it provided for a single evaluation phase, but after approval, it would be converted in a bundle of national patents.
==States parties== The convention was signed by 10 states in 1994, 8 of which became members one year later upon [[ratification]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wipo.int/wipolex/en/other_treaties/parties.jsp?treaty_id=228&group_id=21|title=Treaty database: Eurasian Patent Convention (EAPO)|work=WIPO|accessdate=3 July 2012}}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" |- ! Country ! Signature ! Ratification/Accession ! Denunciation |- | {{flag|Armenia}} | {{dts|9 September 1994}} | {{dts|27 November 1995}} | |- | {{flag|Azerbaijan}} | {{dts|9 September 1994}} | {{dts|25 September 1995}} | |- | {{flag|Belarus}} | {{dts|9 September 1994}} | {{dts|8 May 1995}} | |- | {{flag|Georgia}} | {{dts|9 September 1994}} | | |- | {{flag|Kazakhstan}} | {{dts|9 September 1994}} | {{dts|4 August 1995}} | |- | {{flag|Kyrgyzstan}} | {{dts|9 September 1994}} | {{dts|13 October 1995}} | |- | {{flag|Moldova}} | {{dts|9 September 1994}} | {{dts|16 November 1995}} | {{dts|26 April 2012}}<ref name=pin/> |- | {{flag|Russia}} | {{dts|9 September 1994}} | {{dts|27 June 1995}} | |- | {{flag|Tajikistan}} | {{dts|9 September 1994}} | {{dts|12 May 1995}} | |- | {{flag|Turkmenistan}} | | {{dts|1 March 1995}} | |- | {{flag|Ukraine}} | {{dts|9 September 1994}} | | |}
== Opposition == An opposition can be filed against a Eurasian patent granted under the provisions of the Eurasian Patent Convention within six months from the publication of the granted patent.<ref name=pin/>
== Statistics == "Between 1996 and the end of 2015, approximately 43 700 Eurasian applications were filed and 22 700 Eurasian patents were granted at the EAPO."<ref name=pin/>
