{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}

'''Exempt property''', under the [[law]] of [[property]] in many jurisdictions, is property that can neither be passed by [[will (law)|will]] nor claimed by [[creditor]]s of the deceased in the event that a decedent leaves a surviving spouse or surviving descendants. Typically, exempt property includes a family [[car]], and a certain amount of cash (perhaps $10,000-$20,000), or the equivalent value in personal property.

Exempt property calculations and provisions are determined on a state-by-state basis.  This is important within the bankruptcy process, and may affect an individual's decision to file [[Chapter 7, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 7]] or [[Chapter 13, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 13]] [[bankruptcy]].  State exemptions vary from strict to generous.  For example, [http://www.statutes.legis.state.tx.us/Docs/PR/htm/PR.42.htm Texas property exemptions] are more lenient and include your homestead and up to $60,000 in personal property. Texas also exempts certain investments and insurance policies. Other states, such as Arizona, may exempt only $150 in a checking account comparatively speaking.

